
//module Tests::Physics::Particle;

// stone -emit-module Particle.stone => ./Tests.Physics.Particle.stonemodule 


// The is the file's space in the module Tests.Behavior.Modules.stonemodule 
// So, stone -emit-module -module-name Tests.Physics.Particle => 
// Tests.Behavior.Modules.stonemodule 
// The space name does not have to match the module name. It is just preferrable to do so.
// Suppose you do the following:  -emit-module -module-name Physics => Physics.stonemodule
// Then, you space in the module is Tests.Behavior.Modules.Physics 
//
space Tests.Behavior.Modules.Physics {
	public struct Boson {
	}
}

// Suppose you do the following:  -emit-module -module-name Physics => Physics.stonemodule 
// Then, you do 'using Physics' and you use Electron directly -- Physics.Electron will not work. The module
// is just a container and not an implicit space 
// But, do you want to enforce this where the begining of the space identifier must match the module 
// identifier. So,
public struct Electron {
}

// But, do you want to enforce this where the begining of the space identifier must match the module 
// identifier. So, Physics.stonemodule  => 
space Physics.AnythingElese {
	public struct Proton{
	}
}
// You could also make it implicit => 
// -emit-module -module-name CompanyName.Physics => CompanyName.Physics.stonemodule
space Particle {
	public struct Proton{
	}
}


// To make this simple, I am seeing a pattern here that I prefer and may be the better 
// solution because you will ultimately want to do the following:
// using ProtonAlias = CompanyName.Physics.Proton. So, you cannot get away from the 'real module name'
// Hmm... not really. 


// Explicit => 
// -emit-module -module-name CompanyName.Physics => CompanyName.Physics.stonemodule
space CompanyName.Physics.Particle {
	public struct Quark {
	}
}

// implicit => 
// -emit-module -module-name CompanyName.Physics => CompanyName.Physics.stonemodule
space Particle {
	public struct Proton{
	}
}
// Then, using CompanyName.Physics loads the module; 

// Either way, it seems that it may not matter. Meaning,
// -emit-module -module-name CompanyName.Physics => CompanyName.Physics.stonemodule
// is just the module name and the types can create their own spaces. But, as a convention,
// you will probably do the following: Identifier.stonemodule 

space Tests.Physics {
	public struct Proton { 
	}
}

// Then, using CompanyName.Physics is the module name and you could do:
// using ProtonAlias = Tests.Physics.Proton which now becomes a mess. Uless you do:
// import CompanyName.Physics; then, using refers to spaces inside the module 

